Cut the @red onion{1} in half through the root. Peel and then slice into thin half
moon shapes. Remove the core from the @green pepper{1} and slice as thinly as you
can. Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}. Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}.

Heat a #saucepan{} over medium heat and add a splash of @oil{}. When the oil is
hot, add your onion and pepper. Cook for ~{5%minutes} or until soft. Season with
@salt{} and @black pepper{}. Add half your garlic, @dried thyme{1.5%tsp} and
@ground coriander{1.5%tsp} (the leftovers are for the meatballs, so don't use
them all!). Add all of the @mild paprika{1.5%tbsp}.

Cook your veggies for another ~{2%minutes} and then add the @tomato puree{1} and
@chopped tomatoes{1%400g can}. Bring to the boil, stir in the @beef stock pot{1}
and the @water{200%ml}. Lower the heat to medium and simmer for ~{15-20%minutes}.

Pop the @basmati rice{150%g} into a #pot{} (with a #lid{}). Add the @water{300%ml}.
Bring to the boil on high heat, then lower the heat to medium. Pop the lid on and
leave to simmer for ~{10%minutes}. After 10 mins, remove your rice from the heat
and leave to finish cooking in its own steam for another ~{10%minutes}.

Meanwhile, make the meatballs. Pop the @British beef mince{250%g} into a #bowl{}.
Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} and then add the leftover garlic, dried
thyme and ground coriander. Mix in the @panko breadcrumbs{10%g} and squeeze the
mixture together into one large ball.

Break the large ball into smaller balls (three per person) and roll them well so
as they don't fall apart when you cook them. Pop your meatballs into your sauce to
cook.

> Make sure they are at least half submerged in the sauce.

Pop the lid on (or cover with #foil{}) and let your meatballs cook for
~{10-12%minutes}, until no longer pink in the middle.

> Turn your meatballs over halfway through to make sure they cook evenly.

When your meatballs are cooked, stir in the @baby spinach{1}, pop the lid back on
and cook for another ~{2-3%minutes} or until your spinach has completely wilted.
Taste your sauce and add more salt and black pepper if necessary. Remove from
the heat and stir through two-thirds of the @sour cream{1}.

Fluff up your rice with a #fork{}. Spoon your rice onto your plates and make a
well in the centre. Ladle your beef meatball goulash into the well and finish
with a dollop of sour cream and a sprinkling of parsley.